04492nam a22006855i 9781487574086DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191987onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875740867 a10.3138/97814875740862doi  a(DE-B1597)537062  a(OCoLC)1102655439  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPOL0340002bisacsh04a327.1/72/09711 aSocknat, Thomas P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWitness Against War :bPacifism in Canada, 1900–1945 /cThomas P. Socknat. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1987  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Early pacifist traditions in Canada -- t2. The collapse of liberal pacifism -- t3. Conscription and conscience -- t4. A resurgent peace movement -- t5. In search of peace and social justice -- t6. Crisis and consolidation -- t7. The courage of conviction -- t8. Alternative pacifist service -- t9. Relief and reconciliation -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRallying today to the call for nuclear disarmament, the peace movement in Canada is strong and growing. But it is by no means new. In this study of pacifism during the first half of the twentieth century, Thomas Socknat explores a critical chapter in the Canadian peace movement’s history. Canada’s pacifist heritage, he argues, is rooted in two distinct but complementary traditions, the historic non-resistance of religious sects such as the Mennonites and the liberal Protestant and humanitarian tradition associated with the social reform movement. The First World War radicalized pacifists, and the interwar era saw a resurgent peace movement shaped by a socially radical pacifism. During the Depression a pacifist-socialist alliance appeared to be in the vanguard of Canadian social action. But by the mid-thirties, pacifists found their pursuit of social justice in direct conflict with their commitment to non-violence. As social radicals began to abandon pacifism for the fight against fascism, the Canadian peace movement was severely weakened. Nevertheless, during the Second World War sectarian and non-sectarian pacifists joined in the defence of civil liberties and the individual conscience. Socknat concludes that Canadian pacifists were a small but forceful minority who exercised a dual function in Canada: prophecy of an ideal of peace and reconciliation of social tensions. Above all, in its uncompromising emphasis on questions of conscience, the pacifist witness against war helped preserve those moral principles underlying Canadian culture and laid a solid foundation for the politicized peace movement of the nuclear era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPacifismzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPeacexHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757408640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487574086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487574086.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK